# Express API Patterns

## Route Files

- One router per resource (e.g., `auth.routes.ts`, `habits.routes.ts`)
- Routes only define method + path + middleware chain + controller handler
- Prefix all routes with `/api`

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
import { Router } from 'express';
import { authenticate } from '../middleware/auth';
import { validate } from '../middleware/validate';
import { createHabitSchema } from '../schemas/habit.schema';
import { createHabit, getHabits } from '../controllers/habit.controller';

const router = Router();

router.post('/', authenticate, validate(createHabitSchema), createHabit);
router.get('/', authenticate, getHabits);

export { router as habitRouter };
```

## Controllers

- Keep controllers thin — extract logic into the db/service layer
- Always wrap async handlers to forward errors to Express error middleware
- Return consistent status codes: 200 (ok), 201 (created), 204 (deleted), 400 (validation), 401 (auth), 404 (not found), 500 (server)

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: thin controller with async wrapper
export const createHabit = asyncHandler(async (req: AuthRequest, res: Response) => {
  const habit = await insertHabit(req.user.id, req.body);
  res.status(201).json({ data: habit });
});
```

## Middleware

- `authenticate` — verify JWT, attach `user` to `req`
- `validate(schema)` — run Zod schema on `req.body`, return 400 on failure
- Global error handler as the last middleware — catches all thrown/forwarded errors
